1340
01:55:41,100 --> 01:55:45,100
You can think of material systems as a stack.

1341
01:55:45,100 --> 01:55:53,100
And what Material X does is it defines a standard set of nodes you could use to create a material graph from.

1342
01:55:53,100 --> 01:55:57,100
But the implementation of each node is not defined by Material X.

1343
01:55:57,100 --> 01:56:01,100
You have to go implement it for each target system renderer.

1344
01:56:01,100 --> 01:56:07,100
If it's HLSL, GLSL, OSL, and whatnot.

1345
01:56:07,100 --> 01:56:18,100
MDL is a material definition language that is actually hyper-focused on physical accuracy.

1346
01:56:18,100 --> 01:56:21,100
It doesn't define any nodes or any particular things.

1347
01:56:21,100 --> 01:56:26,100
So you can go implement Material X nodes with MDL.

1348
01:56:26,100 --> 01:56:36,100
But it can compile to many other languages like HLSL, GLSL, OSL, C++, CUDA, so on and so forth.

1349
01:56:36,100 --> 01:56:38,100
So you can combine the two there.

1350
01:56:38,100 --> 01:56:40,100
But MDL does something else.

1351
01:56:40,100 --> 01:56:43,100
It's constrained to physical accuracy.

1352
01:56:43,100 --> 01:56:51,100
So it's about energy conservation and bidirectionality in the BSDF models.

1353
01:56:51,100 --> 01:56:54,100
And all of this stuff is assumed in there.

1354
01:56:54,100 --> 01:56:57,100
It's constraining you to only do two things.

1355
01:56:57,100 --> 01:56:59,100
You can only do two things, really.

1356
01:56:59,100 --> 01:57:05,100
Define what the light transport is in your material at a given point.

1357
01:57:05,100 --> 01:57:10,100
And patterns that allow you to parameterize different aspects of this light transport.

1358
01:57:10,100 --> 01:57:12,100
That's the two things that it does.

1359
01:57:12,100 --> 01:57:18,100
And because it only does that and it's a language specified to that, it's not really Turing complete.

1360
01:57:18,100 --> 01:57:23,100
